, also **Utsuro-fune,** and **Urobune**, was an unknown object that allegedly washed ashore in 1803 in [province](Hitachi)(Hitachi province) on the eastern coast of [Japan](Japan). When defining Utsuro-bune, the bune part means "boat" while Utsuro means empty, or hollow. Accounts of the tale appear in four texts: *Oushuku Zakki* (1815), *Toen shōsetsu* (1825), *Hyōryū kishū* (1835) and *Ume-no-chiri* (1844).

According to [legend](legend), a young woman aged 18–20 years old, arrived on a local beach aboard the "hollow ship" on February 22, 1803. Fishermen brought her inland to investigate further, but the woman was unable to communicate in [Japanese](Japanese language). She was very different from anyone else there. The fishermen then returned her and her vessel to the sea, where it drifted away.

[Historian](Historian)s, [ethnologists](ethnology) and [physicist](physicist)s such as [Tanaka](Kazuo)(Kazuo Tanaka) and [Kunio](Yanagita)(Yanagita Kunio) have evaluated the "legend of the hollow boat" as part of a long-standing tradition within Japanese [folklore](folklore).Kunio Yanagita, Fanny Hagin Mayer, Nihon Hōsō Kyōkai: *The Yanagita Kunio guide to the Japanese folk tale*. Indiana University Press, Bloomington (IN) 1986, , p. 176–178. Alternatively, certain [ufologists](Ufology) have claimed that the story represents evidence for a [encounter](close)(close encounter) with extraterrestrial life.

The term "Utsuro-bune" in Japanese roughly translates to "hollow boat" or "empty boat," with "Utsuro" meaning "empty" or "hollow," and "bune" meaning "boat." It refers to an unknown object that reportedly washed ashore in Japan in 1803, associated with legends and folklore, and has also been interpreted by some ufologists as evidence of extraterrestrial encounters.

## Controversies

*Fallout 76* Power Armor [edition](special)(special edition) drew controversy upon release. Bethesda advertised that the edition would include a [canvas](canvas) [bag](duffel)(duffel bag), but a [nylon](nylon) one was included instead. Responding to customer complaints, Bethesda claimed that the bag had to be changed due to unavailability of materials, and initially stated the intention to take no action. The publisher received criticism for not making the change known beforehand, with *[Eurogamer](Eurogamer)* pointing out that the bag's description on Bethesda's website had only changed to read "nylon" after complaints had been submitted. Bethesda later offered affected customers free in-game currency of 500 atoms as compensation, equivalent to . Critics pointed out this amount of currency was not enough to purchase the in-game postman uniform (700 atoms), which includes a canvas bag. Additionally, it was discovered that Bethesda had produced a different *Fallout 76*–themed canvas bag and given them for free to [influencers](online)(Internet celebrity), further adding to the fan outrage. Bethesda announced on December 3, 2018, that they would be producing canvas bags for all owners of the Power Armor special edition, which were ultimately said to be shipping "in four to six months." In June 2019, the bags were delivered to customers.

A [breach](data)(data breach) occurred on December 5, 2018, when a [glitch](glitch) in Bethesda's [system](support)(Issue tracking system) revealed personal information of approximately 65 *Fallout 76* customers who had submitted a support ticket to receive the canvas bag. Users were able to open and close tickets of other customers and view personal information, including names, addresses, emails and partial credit card information. In a statement given to *[Technica](Ars)(Ars Technica)*, Bethesda said that the breach occurred via "an error with our customer support website" and that they are "investigating the incident and will provide additional updates as we learn more". The publisher clarified that the only information leaked were details that the support site would have requested, rather than credit card numbers or passwords, and that they would notify all affected customers.

In 2018, Bethesda partnered with the Silver Screen Bottling Company to create "Nuka Dark Rum", an alcoholic beverage based on the in-game "Nuka-Cola Dark" introduced in the *[4: Nuka-World](Fallout)(Fallout 4: Nuka-World)* [add-on](Downloadable content). The rum was available to be pre-ordered in August 2018 for . While its release was expected to coincide with the launch of *Fallout 76*, the rum was delayed and was shipped instead in late December 2018. Upon receiving it, fans criticized the fact that the rum bottle advertised, previously expected to be a bottle in the missile-like shape of the in-game Nuka-Cola item, had turned out to be a standard glass bottle encased in a large plastic cover. The rum's asking price of $80 was subsequently condemned from expectations that the design would be of high quality, since none of the marketing had stated what the bottles would be made of.

In September 2019, collectible "Nuka Cola"–themed *Fallout* helmets produced by Chronicle Collectibles, of which only 32 of the 20,000 manufactured were sold, were recalled by the [Consumer Product Safety Commission](U.S.)(U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission) due to containing high levels of mold and posing a health risk. No incidents or injuries were reported. [GameStop](GameStop), which sold the helmets, notified all customers who had purchased a helmet and offered them a full refund.

In June 2022, a *Kotaku* article published reports from ten anonymous former employees of Bethesda and its parent company [Media](ZeniMax)(ZeniMax Media) of severe mismanagement during *Fallout 76*s development. The reports claimed that [crunch](Crunch (video games)) had been enforced, leading to an "exodus" of senior developers from the company. The loss of staff led to Bethesda borrowing developers working on [Studios](Arkane)(Arkane Studios)' *[Redfall](Redfall)* and Bethesda's *[Starfield](Starfield (video game))* to assist with *Fallout 76*. Other alleged issues included technical problems with the game's design and engine, as well as these concerns being ignored by senior management. The sources expressed cynicism towards an improvement of working conditions at Bethesda (following their acquisition by Microsoft), saying "It would be great if something like [ABetterABK](ABK Workers Alliance) existed for Bethesda [...] But everyone is terrified...because [Bethesda] HR is super cutthroat."

The controversy involving the Fallout 76 Power Armor edition's physical item centered around a discrepancy between what was advertised and what was actually provided. Bethesda promised that the edition would include a canvas bag, but instead, a nylon bag was included. This change was not communicated to customers beforehand, leading to criticism. Bethesda initially claimed that the change was due to material shortages and stated they would take no action. However, after customer complaints, Bethesda offered affected customers 500 in-game atoms as compensation, which was considered insufficient by many players, especially since the in-game item it could buy (a postman uniform including a canvas bag) cost more than the compensation. Additionally, it was revealed that Bethesda had produced and given away a different Fallout-themed canvas bag to influencers, which further fueled outrage among fans. Eventually, Bethesda announced that they would produce canvas bags for all owners of the edition, which started shipping in June 2019.

## History

In 1781, [Wilhelm Scheele](Carl)(Carl Wilhelm Scheele) discovered that a new [acid](acid), [acid](tungstic)(tungstic acid), could be made from [scheelite](scheelite) (at the time called tungsten).Scheele, Carl Wilhelm (1781) ["Tungstens bestånds-delar"](https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nyp.33433012786798;view=1up;seq=99) (Tungsten's constituents), *Kungliga Vetenskaps Academiens Nya Handlingar* (Royal Scientific Academy's New Proceedings), **2** : 89–95 (in Swedish).English translation on [pp. 4–13](https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nnc1.cu61255840;view=1up;seq=12) of: de Luyart, John Joseph and Fausto, with Charles Cullen, trans., [*A Chemical Analysis of Wolfram and Examination of a New Metal, Which Enters its Composition*](https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nnc1.cu61255840;view=1up;seq=7) (London, England, G. Nicol, 1785). Scheele and [Bergman](Torbern)(Torbern Bergman) suggested that it might be possible to obtain a new metal by reducing this acid. In 1783, [José](Juan José Elhuyar) and [Elhuyar](Fausto)(Fausto Elhuyar) found an acid made from [wolframite](wolframite) that was identical to tungstic acid. Later that year, at the [Basque Society](Royal)(Real Sociedad Bascongada de Amigos del País) in the town of [Bergara](Bergara), Spain, the brothers succeeded in isolating tungsten by reduction of this acid with [charcoal](charcoal), and they are credited with the discovery of the element (they called it "wolfram" or "volfram").de Luyart, J.J. and F. (September 1783) "Análisis químico del volfram, y examen de un nuevo metal, que entra en su composición" (Chemical analysis of wolframite, and examination of a new metal, which enters into its composition), *Extractos de las Juntas Generales celebradas por la Real Sociedad Bascongada de los Amigos del País en la ciudad de Vitoria por setiembre de 1783*, pp. 46–88.de Luyart, John Joseph and Fausto, with Charles Cullen, trans., [*A Chemical Analysis of Wolfram and Examination of a New Metal, Which Enters its Composition*](https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=nnc1.cu61255840;view=1up;seq=7) (London, England, G. Nicol, 1785).Caswell, Lyman R. and Stone Daley, Rebecca W. (1999) "The Delhuyar brothers, tungsten, and Spanish silver," *Bulletin for the History of Chemistry*, **23** : 11–19. Available at: [University of Illinois (USA)](http://www.scs.illinois.edu/~mainzv/HIST/bulletin_open_access/num23/num23%20p11-19.pdf)

The strategic value of tungsten came to notice in the early 20th century. British authorities acted in 1912 to free the [mine](Carrock)(Carrock Fell) from the German owned Cumbrian Mining Company and, during [War I](World)(World War I), restrict German access elsewhere. In [War II](World)(World War II), tungsten played a more significant role in [political dealings.](background)(Wolfram Crisis) Portugal, as the main European source of the element, was [under pressure from both sides](put)(Portugal during World War II#Wolfram (Tungsten)), because of its deposits of wolframite ore at [Panasqueira](Panasqueira). Tungsten's desirable properties such as resistance to high temperatures, its hardness and density, and its strengthening of alloys made it an important raw material for the arms industry, both as a constituent of weapons and equipment and employed in production itself, e.g., in [carbide](tungsten)(tungsten carbide) cutting tools for machining steel.

Now tungsten is used in many more applications such as aircraft & motorsport ballast weights, darts, anti-vibration tooling, and sporting equipment.

Tungsten is unique amongst the elements in that it has been the subject of patent proceedings. In 1928, a US court rejected [Electric](General)(General Electric)'s attempt to patent it, overturning  granted in 1913 to [D. Coolidge](William)(William D. Coolidge).General Electric Co. v. De Forest Radio Co., 28 F.2d 641, 643 (3rd Cir. 1928)

The **Wright brothers**, **Orville Wright** (August 19, 1871 – January 30, 1948) and **Wilbur Wright** (April 16, 1867 – May 30, 1912), were American [aviation](aviation) pioneers generally credited with inventing, building, and flying the world's first successful motor-operated [airplane](airplane). They made the first controlled, sustained flight of a powered, [aircraft](heavier-than-air)(Aircraft#Heavier-than-air – aerodynes) with the *[Flyer](Wright)(Wright Flyer)* on December 17, 1903, four miles (6 km) south of [Hawk, North Carolina](Kitty)(Kitty Hawk, North Carolina), at what is now known as [Devil Hills](Kill)(Kill Devil Hills, North Carolina). The brothers were also the first to invent [controls](aircraft)(Aircraft flight control system) that made fixed-wing [flight](powered)(powered flight) possible.

In 1904–1905, the Wright brothers developed their flying machine to make longer-running and more aerodynamic flights with the [Flyer II](Wright)(Wright Flyer II), followed by the first truly practical [aircraft](fixed-wing)(fixed-wing aircraft), the [Flyer III](Wright)(Wright Flyer III). The brothers' breakthrough was their creation of a [control system](three-axis)(Flight dynamics (aircraft)), which enabled the pilot to steer the aircraft effectively and to maintain its equilibrium. This method remains standard on fixed-wing aircraft of all kinds.Howard 1988, p. 89. From the beginning of their aeronautical work, Wilbur and Orville focused on developing a reliable method of pilot control as the key to solving "the flying problem". This approach differed significantly from other experimenters of the time who put more emphasis on developing powerful engines.Mortimer 2009, p. 2. Using a small home-built [tunnel](wind)(wind tunnel), the Wrights also collected more accurate data than any before, enabling them to design more efficient wings and propellers. Their first U.S. patent did not claim invention of a flying machine, but rather a system of aerodynamic control that manipulated a flying machine's surfaces.

The brothers gained the mechanical skills essential to their success by working for years in their [Ohio](Dayton,)(Dayton, Ohio)-based shop with printing presses, bicycles, motors, and other machinery. Their work with bicycles, in particular, influenced their belief that an unstable vehicle such as a flying machine could be controlled and balanced with practice. This was a trend, as many other aviation pioneers were also dedicated cyclists and involved in the bicycle business in various ways. From 1900 until their first powered flights in late 1903, the brothers conducted extensive [tests](glider)(Glider (aircraft)#19th century) that also developed their skills as pilots. Their shop mechanic [Taylor](Charles)(Charlie Taylor (mechanic)) became an important part of the team, building their first airplane engine in close collaboration with the brothers.

The Wright brothers' status as inventors of the airplane has been subject to counter-claims by various parties. Much controversy persists over the many [claims of early aviators](competing)(Claims to the first powered flight). Edward Roach, historian for the [Aviation Heritage National Historical Park](Dayton)(Dayton Aviation Heritage National Historical Park), argues that they were excellent self-taught engineers who could run a small company, but they did not have the business skills or temperament to dominate the growing aviation industry.Roach, Edward J. The Wright Company: From Invention to Industry. Athens, Ohio: Ohio University Press, 2014. , page 2.
The two brothers credited with the isolation of tungsten as a metal in 1783 are the Elhuyar brothers, José and Fausto Elhuyar.

**Ryzen** ( ) is a brand of [multi-core](multi-core processor) [x86-64](x86-64) [microprocessor](microprocessor)s designed and marketed by [AMD](AMD) for desktop, mobile, server, and embedded platforms based on the [microarchitecture](Zen)(Zen (microarchitecture)). AMD announced a new series of processors on December 13, 2016, named "Ryzen", and delivered them in Q1 2017, the first of several generations. The 1000 series featured up to eight cores and 16 threads, with a 52% [per cycle](instructions)(instructions per cycle) (IPC) increase over their prior CPU products. The second generation of Ryzen processors, the Ryzen 2000 series, released in April 2018, featured the [Zen+](Zen+) microarchitecture, a [12 nm](Die shrink#Half-shrink) process ([GlobalFoundries](GlobalFoundries)); the aggregate performance increased 10% (of which approximately 3% was IPC, 6% was frequency); most importantly, Zen+ fixed the cache and memory latencies that had been major weak points (for latency-sensitive workloads, IPC gains of nearly ≈10%). The third generation of Ryzen processors launched on July 7, 2019, based on AMD's [2](Zen)(Zen 2) architecture, featuring significant design improvements with a 15% average IPC boost, a doubling of floating point capability to a full 256 bit wide execution datapath much like [Intel](Intel)'s [Haswell](Haswell (microarchitecture)) released in 2014, a shift to an [MCM](Multi-chip module) style "chiplet" based package design, and a further shrink to Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company's ([TSMC](TSMC)) [nm](7)(7 nm process) fabrication process. On June 16, 2020, AMD announced new Ryzen 3000 series XT processors with 100 MHz higher boost clocks versus non XT processors. On October 8, 2020, AMD announced the Zen 3 architecture for their Ryzen 5000 series processors, featuring a 19% [per cycle](instructions)(instructions per cycle) (IPC) improvement over Zen 2, while being built on the same 7 nm TSMC node with out-of-the-box operating boost frequencies exceeding 5 GHz for the first time since AMD's Piledriver.Archived at [Ghostarchive](https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211205/iuiO6rqYV4o) and the [Wayback Machine](https://web.archive.org/web/20201008030113/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iuiO6rqYV4o):  AMD Ryzen Desktop Processors |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iuiO6rqYV4o |website=YouTube |language=en-US |access-date=November 28, 2022}} With the launch of Zen 3 via the Ryzen 5000 series, AMD took the lead in gaming performance over Intel, particularly with single-threaded performance. This was followed by an unusually short stop-gap release of Ryzen 6000 mobile-only series processors on January 4, 2022, using the modestly changed Zen3+ core on a 6nm process by TSMC, with claims up to 15% performance uplift (typical 10% performance) gains (stated to be from frequency rather than IPC). Following this, the Ryzen 7000 series released on September 27, 2022, for desktops, featuring the new Zen4 core with a 13% uplift in IPC and 15% increase in frequency for a claimed nearly 30% in single thread performance. The Ryzen 7000 series features a brand new AM5 socket that only supports [SDRAM](DDR5)(DDR5 SDRAM), unlike AMD's previous DDR3 sockets like AM2/+ and AM3/+ that offered DDR2 and DDR3 options and Intel's Alder Lake platforms that offer both DDR4 and DDR5 compatibility.

A majority of AMD's consumer Ryzen products use the [AM4](Socket)(Socket AM4) platform. In August 2017, AMD launched their Ryzen Threadripper line aimed at the enthusiast workstation market. AMD Ryzen Threadripper uses the larger [TR4](Socket TR4), [sTRX4](Socket sTRX4), and [sWRX8](Socket sWRX8) sockets, which support additional memory channels and [Express](PCI)(PCI Express) lanes. AMD has moved to the new [AM5](Socket)(Socket AM5) platform for consumer desktop Ryzen with the release of [4](Zen)(Zen 4) products in late 2022.

**Russian-occupied territories of Ukraine** are areas of [Ukraine](Ukraine) that are currently controlled by [Russia](Russia) in the course of the [War](Russo-Ukrainian)(Russo-Ukrainian War). In Ukrainian law, they are defined as the "temporarily occupied territories of Ukraine" ().

The occupation started in 2014 following [invasion and annexation](Russia's)(Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation) of the [peninsula](Crimean)(Crimea), and its assisting the forces of the mostly unrecognized [Donetsk](Donetsk People's Republic) and [Luhansk](Luhansk People's Republic) People's Republics in capturing parts of the [Donetsk](Donetsk Oblast) and [Luhansk](Luhansk Oblast) [oblasts](Oblasts of Ukraine) during the [in Donbas](war)(War in Donbas (2014–2022)). In 2022, Russian forces initiated [full-scale invasion](a)(2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine) of the nation and successfully occupied more territory throughout the country. However, due to continued fierce Ukrainian resistance, coupled with logistical challenges (*e.g.* the stalled [Kyiv convoy](Russian)(Russian Kyiv convoy)), the [Armed Forces](Russian)(Russian Armed Forces) announced their withdrawal from [Chernihiv](Russian occupation of Chernihiv Oblast), [Kyiv](Russian occupation of Kyiv Oblast), [Sumy](Russian occupation of Sumy Oblast), and [Zhytomyr](Russian occupation of Zhytomyr Oblast) oblasts in early April.

In early September 2022, Ukrainian forces ended the months-long stalemate on the front lines with [successful counteroffensive in the Kharkiv region](a)(2022 Kharkiv counteroffensive), inflicting a major defeat on Russian forces by forcing their retreat. Then later in November, Ukrainian forces once again achieved a major success with a [counteroffensive](southern)(2022 Kherson counteroffensive) retaking the city of [Kherson](Kherson) on 11 November.

On 30 September 2022, Russia announced [annexation of Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk and Zaporizhzhia oblasts](the)(Russian annexation of Donetsk, Kherson, Luhansk and Zaporizhzhia oblasts), despite only occupying part of the claimed territory. The UN General Assembly responded by passing [resolution](a)(United Nations General Assembly Resolution ES-11/4) rejecting this annexation as illegal and upholding Ukraine's right to territorial integrity.

Before 2022, Russia occupied  of Ukrainian territory (Crimea, and parts of Donetsk and Luhansk), and occupied an additional  after its full-scale invasion by March 2022, a total of  or almost 27% of Ukraine's territory. By 11 November, the [for the Study of War](Institute)(Institute for the Study of War) calculated that Ukrainian forces had liberated an area of  from Russian occupation, leaving Russia with control of about 18% of Ukraine's territory.
The Ukrainian city that was recaptured by Ukrainian forces on 11 November 2022 during the Kherson counteroffensive is Kherson.

**American Express Company** (**Amex**) is an American multinational financial services corporation that specializes in [cards](payment)(payment card industry). Headquartered in [York City](New)(New York City), it is one of the [valuable companies in the world](most)(List of S&P 500 companies) and one of the 30 components of the [Jones Industrial Average](Dow)(Dow Jones Industrial Average). The company's [logo](logo), adopted in 1958, is a [gladiator](gladiator) or [centurion](centurion), whose image appears on the company's well-known [cheques](traveler's)(Traveller's cheque), charge cards, and [card](credit)(credit card)s. It is based in the [Express Tower](American)(200 Vesey Street), located in the [Park City](Battery)(Battery Park City) neighborhood of [Manhattan](Lower)(Lower Manhattan), where it maintains its corporate offices. The company is the largest provider of traveler's cheques worldwide.

Founded in 1850 as an [mail](express)(express mail) dispatcher, the company introduced financial and travel services to clientele during the early 1900s. American Express developed their first paper [card](charge)(charge card) in 1958, gold card in 1966, green card in 1969, platinum card in 1984, and [card](centurion)(Centurion Card) in 1999. The "Don't Leave Home Without It" [campaign](ad)(Advertising campaign) was introduced in 1975 and renewed in 2005. During the 1980s, the firm invested and divested in the brokerage industry, through a stake in [Lehman Hutton](Shearson)(Shearson). In the 1990s, they discontinued cutting [fees](interchange)(interchange fee) for merchants who exclusively accepted their cards and expanded their market share through [marketing campaigns](targeted)(#Advertising campaigns). They converted into a bank holding company during the [financial crisis](2008)(2007–2008 financial crisis). The firm launched their [lounge](airport)(airport lounge) amenity in 2013.

American Express accounts for 22.9% of the total dollar volume of domestic credit card transactions (as of 2016) with 56.4million cards in force in the U.S. and 121.7million cards globally (as of 2021). The average cardholder spends $23,496 annually. In 2017, *[Forbes](Forbes)* named American Express the most valuable brand in global financial services, and 23rd overall, with an estimated [value](brand)(Brand valuation) of US$24.5billion. In 2020, *[Fortune](Fortune (magazine))* magazine placed the company ninth in their list of Top 100 Companies to Work For feature, based on an employee survey of satisfaction.
The American Express card introduced in 1999 that is often referred to as the 'black card' is the Centurion Card, also known as the Black Card.

[ship](Cruise)(Cruise ship)s are large [ship](passenger)(passenger ship)s used mainly for vacationing. Unlike [liner](ocean)(ocean liner)s, they typically embark on round-trip voyages to various ports-of-call, where passengers may go on [tours](Tourism) known as "shore excursions". They may carry thousands of passengers in a single trip, and are some of the largest ships in the world by the [tonnage](gross)(gross tonnage)(GT), bigger than many [ships](cargo)(List of largest container ships). Cruise ships started to exceed ocean liners in size and capacity in the mid-1990s; before then, few were more than 50,000GT. In the decades since, the size of the largest vessels has more than doubled. There have been nine or more new cruise ships added every year since 2001, most of which are 100,000GT or greater. In the two decades between 1988 and 2009, the largest cruise ships grew a third longer (268 m to 360 m), almost doubled their widths (32.2 m to 60.5 m), doubled the total passengers (2,744 to 5,400), and tripled in volume (73,000 GT to 225,000 GT). , the largest cruise ship, , has a gross tonnage of 236,857, is  long,  wide, and holds up to 6,988 passengers.

Cruise ships are organized much like floating hotels, with a complete hospitality staff in addition to the usual ship's crew. Modern cruise ships, while sacrificing some qualities of [seaworthiness](seakeeping), have added amenities to cater to [tourists](nautical)(nautical tourism), with recent vessels being described as "balcony-laden floating condominiums". The "megaships" went from a single deck with verandas to all decks with verandas, and feature ameneties such as theaters, fine-dining and chain restaurants, spas, fitness centers, casinos, sports facilities, and even amusement park attractions.

Cruise ships require electricity for powering both hotel services and for [propulsion](Marine propulsion). Cruise ships are designed with all the heavy machinery at the bottom of the ship and lightweight materials at the top, making them inherently stable even as ship designs are getting taller and taller, and most passenger ships utilize [fins](stabilizer)(Stabilizer (ship)) to further reduce rolling of tall ships in heavy weather. While some cruise ships use traditional fixed [propeller](propeller)s and [rudder](rudder)s to steer, most larger ships use propellers that can swivel left and right to steer the ship, known as [thruster](azimuth)(azimuth thruster)s, which allow even the largest ship designs to have adequate maneuverability.

Cruise ships are operated by [line](cruise)(cruise line)s, which are [companies](company) that market cruises to the public. In the 1990s, many cruise lines were bought by much larger holding companies and continue to operate as brands or subsidiaries of the holding company. For instance, [Corporation & plc](Carnival)(Carnival Corporation & plc) owns both the [mass-market](Mass market) [Cruise Line](Carnival)(Carnival Cruise Line), focused on larger party ships for younger travelers, and [America Line](Holland)(Holland America Line), whose smaller ships cultivate an image of classic elegance. The common practice in the cruise industry in ship sales and orders is to list the smaller operating company, not the larger holding corporation, as the recipient cruise line of the ship.
As of 2023, the largest cruise ship is the "Wonder of the Seas," with a gross tonnage of 236,857 GT.

The **unicursal hexagram** is a [hexagram](hexagram) or six-pointed star that can be traced or drawn [unicursally](unicursal curve), in one continuous line rather than by two overlaid triangles. It is often depicted in an interlaced form with the lines of the hexagram passing over and under one another to form a [knot](knot (mathematics)). It is a specific instance of the far more general shape discussed in [Pascal](Blaise)(Blaise Pascal)'s 1639 *[Mysticum](Hexagrammum)(Hexagrammum Mysticum)*.

### Contemporary regulations

[[sign warning about the presence of bears. The Norwegian text translates into "Applies to all of Svalbard".](File:Polar-Bear-Warning-Longyearbyen.jpg|thumb|right|Road)]

Concerns over the future survival of the species led to the development of national regulations on polar bear hunting, beginning in the mid-1950s. The Soviet Union banned all hunting in 1956. Canada began imposing hunting quotas in 1968. Norway passed a series of increasingly strict regulations from 1965 to 1973, and has completely banned hunting since then. The United States began regulating hunting in 1971 and adopted the [Mammal Protection Act](Marine)(Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972) in 1972. In 1973, the [Agreement on the Conservation of Polar Bears](International)(International Agreement on the Conservation of Polar Bears) was signed by all five nations whose territory is inhabited by polar bears: Canada, Denmark, Norway, the [Union](Soviet)(Soviet Union), and the United States. Member countries agreed to place restrictions on recreational and commercial hunting, ban hunting from aircraft and icebreakers, and conduct further research.[International Agreement on the Conservation of Polar Bears](https://web.archive.org/web/20030409113042/http://pbsg.npolar.no/ConvAgree/agreement.htm), 15 November 1973, Oslo The treaty allows hunting "by local people using traditional methods". Norway is the only country of the five in which all harvest of polar bears is banned. The agreement was a rare case of international cooperation during the [War](Cold)(Cold War). Biologist [Stirling](Ian)(Ian Stirling (biologist)) commented, "For many years, the conservation of polar bears was the only subject in the entire Arctic that nations from both sides of the Iron Curtain could agree upon sufficiently to sign an agreement. Such was the intensity of human fascination with this magnificent predator, the only marine bear."[Ian](Stirling,)(Ian Stirling (biologist)) *Foreword* in

Agreements have been made between countries to co-manage their shared polar bear subpopulations. After several years of negotiations, Russia and the United States signed an agreement in October 2000 to jointly set quotas for indigenous subsistence hunting in Alaska and [Chukotka](Chukotka Autonomous Okrug). The treaty was ratified in October 2007. In September 2015, the polar bear range states agreed upon a "circumpolar action plan" describing their conservation strategy for polar bears.

The species is listed in Appendix II of the [on International Trade in Endangered Species](Convention)(Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species) (CITES) meaning international trade, including in parts or derivatives, is controlled by the CITES system of permits and certificates. The United States government has proposed that polar bears be transferred to Appendix I of [CITES](CITES) which would ban all commercial international trade in polar bear parts. The decision to leave the species listed under Appendix II was endorsed by the IUCN and [TRAFFIC](TRAFFIC), who determined that such an uplisting was unlikely to confer a conservation benefit.
The five nations that are signatories of the Agreement on the Conservation of Polar Bears are Canada, Denmark (Greenland), Norway, Russia, and the United States.
